  <h1>Who Can File a Wrongful Death Claim by State</h1>
  <p class="byline">By our editorial team &mdash; Survivor &amp; Estate Damages. Reviewed May 2026.</p>

  <p>Standing &mdash; the legal authority to bring the claim &mdash; varies significantly across states. This matters early because survivors who try to file without proper standing have their cases dismissed, and the right to refile may be foreclosed by statute of limitations. This guide explains the three structural models and gives a state-by-state overview.</p>

  <h2>The three structural models</h2>

  <h3>Personal representative model (majority of states)</h3>
  <p>The claim is brought by the personal representative of the decedent's estate &mdash; the executor named in the will or, if there's no will, the administrator appointed by the probate court. The personal representative sues "for the use and benefit of" the statutory beneficiaries (typically surviving spouse, children, sometimes parents). Recovery is held by the estate or distributed directly to the beneficiaries per the wrongful death statute.</p>
  <p><strong>States in this group include:</strong> California, Texas (mixed; see below), Illinois, Pennsylvania, Ohio, Michigan, Georgia, North Carolina, Virginia, Massachusetts, Arizona, Colorado, Wisconsin, Indiana, Maryland, Minnesota, Missouri, Tennessee, Oregon, Washington, and most others.</p>
  <p>The practical implication: even if the surviving spouse is clearly the person harmed, they cannot simply file in their own name. The estate must first be opened in probate, a personal representative must be appointed, and that representative becomes the named plaintiff.</p>

  <h3>Direct-beneficiary model (minority of states)</h3>
  <p>The statutory beneficiaries (usually the surviving spouse, then children, then parents in priority order) have direct standing to file without needing a probate appointment. This is simpler in cases with a clear single beneficiary; more complicated when multiple beneficiaries disagree about strategy.</p>
  <p><strong>Examples:</strong> Florida (personal representative, but the underlying claim runs to the survivors); Texas allows certain heirs to file directly under specific circumstances; a handful of others.</p>

  <h3>Hybrid model</h3>
  <p>Some states allow either approach, or require personal representative filing but permit direct filing by survivors under certain conditions (e.g., if no probate is opened within a specified period).</p>

  <h2>Statutory beneficiaries</h2>
  <p>Even where the personal representative files, the recovery flows to the statutory beneficiaries defined by the wrongful death statute, not to the estate generally. Beneficiary classes typically follow this hierarchy:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Surviving spouse and children.</strong> Usually share the recovery, with the proportions specified by statute or by court allocation based on individual loss.</li>
    <li><strong>Parents,</strong> if there is no surviving spouse or children.</li>
    <li><strong>Other dependents,</strong> in some states &mdash; siblings, grandchildren, dependent partners or relatives.</li>
    <li><strong>The estate generally,</strong> in some states, if there are no statutory beneficiaries in the higher classes.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>Some specifics:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Unmarried partners.</strong> Most states do not give standing to unmarried partners, even if they were financially dependent. Some states recognize domestic partners or civil unions; same-sex spouses are recognized everywhere following <em>Obergefell</em>.</li>
    <li><strong>Adult children.</strong> Standing varies. Some states give all children equal standing; some require dependency or minor status. Adult children may receive smaller shares of the recovery if they were not financially or emotionally dependent.</li>
    <li><strong>Stepchildren.</strong> Generally lack standing unless legally adopted.</li>
    <li><strong>Posthumous children.</strong> Children conceived but not yet born at the time of death typically have standing in most states.</li>
    <li><strong>Same-sex spouses.</strong> Recognized everywhere as surviving spouses under <em>Obergefell</em>.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What to do first</h2>
  <p>If you may have a wrongful death claim:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Identify the right person to file.</strong> If your state uses the personal-representative model, this means opening probate and getting someone appointed. Don't delay this step; some states won't toll the statute of limitations while probate is pending.</li>
    <li><strong>Identify all statutory beneficiaries.</strong> Surviving spouse, children, parents, and any others in the relevant class.</li>
    <li><strong>Consult an attorney.</strong> Wrongful death is procedurally tricky and the consequences of getting standing wrong are severe. State bar lawyer referral services and the American Association for Justice maintain wrongful-death attorney referral resources.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Common confusion points</h2>

  <h3>"The estate sued" vs. "I sued"</h3>
  <p>Even in personal-representative states, the recovery isn't necessarily an estate asset for general probate distribution. The wrongful death portion typically flows directly to the statutory beneficiaries outside probate, while the survival action (the decedent's own pre-death pain and suffering, medical bills, etc.) generally flows through the estate. Get this allocation right at settlement time &mdash; it affects taxes, creditor claims, and probate distribution.</p>

  <h3>Multiple potential plaintiffs</h3>
  <p>When a will names one executor but multiple statutory beneficiaries disagree about strategy, the personal representative still controls the litigation but has fiduciary duties to all beneficiaries. Disputes can be brought to probate court for resolution.</p>

  <h3>No will, contested administration</h3>
  <p>If there's no will and multiple potential administrators, probate court appoints. The wrongful death timeline doesn't pause during the dispute, so the parties have an incentive to resolve administration quickly or seek a special administrator for the limited purpose of the wrongful death claim.</p>

  <p>For the timing constraints that make all this urgent, see <a href="/guides/wrongful-death-statute-of-limitations">statute of limitations</a>. For what's recoverable once standing is established, see <a href="/guides/economic-damages-in-wrongful-death-cases">economic damages</a> and <a href="/guides/non-economic-damages-in-wrongful-death">non-economic damages</a>.</p>
